## 8. Technical Approach

Quantir will use a modular architecture for the Aptos integration.

The technical approach includes:

- Researching public Aptos ecosystem data sources.
- Mapping relevant DeFi, RWA, payments, and infrastructure signals.
- Designing normalized signal and alert schemas.
- Building an Aptos adapter for selected public or opt-in signals.
- Implementing risk scoring and explainable alert logic.
- Delivering sample alerts and validation scenarios.
- Providing API/WebSocket or dashboard-facing examples.
- Publishing documentation for developers and reviewers.

The first version will focus on monitoring and alerting. It will not custody user funds, request private keys, execute transactions, or modify protocol contracts.

## 9. Open Source Plan

Grant-funded schemas, documentation, sample alerts, and selected adapter components will be published openly where appropriate.

Quantir’s hosted infrastructure and commercial services may remain separate, but the grant deliverables will be designed to be transparent, reusable, and useful for Aptos ecosystem builders.

## 10. Business Model

Quantir’s long-term business model is based on B2B monitoring, API access, dashboards, custom risk reporting, hosted alerting workflows, and enterprise integrations for protocols, funds, wallets, infrastructure teams, and ecosystem operators.

The grant will help Quantir build the Aptos-specific module and validate the initial use cases. Over time, the Aptos integration can be maintained as part of Quantir’s broader multichain risk intelligence platform.

